"# Chapter 6 — Bytevectors

A bytevector is a fixed-length sequence of unsigned 8-bit integers.
Each cell is a number from 0 to 255. That is the entire type.

## Why bytevectors exist

Most of the time you'll reach for strings or lists. But sometimes you
need to speak the language of BYTES:

- Encoding text for network transmission (UTF-8 is bytes).
- Talking to a binary file format (PNG, WAV, custom protocols).
- Cryptographic operations (hashes, ciphers work on bytes).
- Efficient storage of numeric data where each value fits in 0-255.

R7RS §6.9 gives Motoi ten verbs for building, reading, and writing
bytevectors.

## Problem 1 — Build a bytevector

Two ways: `bytevector` with the bytes as arguments, or `make-bytevector`
with a length and a fill value.

```
(display (bytevector 72 105))
;; => #u8(72 105)

(display (make-bytevector 3 0))
;; => #u8(0 0 0)

(display (make-bytevector 5 255))
;; => #u8(255 255 255 255 255)
```

Read the shape: `#u8(...)` is Motoi's printed form for a bytevector.
Every element is a byte — an integer between 0 and 255.

## Problem 2 — Read and write bytes

`bytevector-u8-ref` reads a byte at an index; `bytevector-u8-set!`
writes.

```
(define bv (bytevector 10 20 30 40))

(display (bytevector-u8-ref bv 0))
;; => 10
(display (bytevector-u8-ref bv 2))
;; => 30

(bytevector-u8-set! bv 0 99)
(display bv)
;; => #u8(99 20 30 40)
```

`bytevector-length` gives the count:

```
(display (bytevector-length bv))
;; => 4
```

## Problem 3 — UTF-8 round-trip

The most common reason to reach for bytevectors is UTF-8 encoding of
strings. `string->utf8` converts a string to its UTF-8 byte
representation; `utf8->string` reverses.

```
(display (string->utf8 \"hi\"))
;; => #u8(104 105)

(display (utf8->string (bytevector 104 105)))
;; => \"hi\"
```

For ASCII strings the bytes are just the codepoints:

```
(display (string->utf8 \"A\"))
;; => #u8(65)
```

Multi-byte UTF-8 becomes multi-byte:

```
(display (string->utf8 \"é\"))
;; => #u8(195 169)   ; é is C3 A9 in UTF-8
```

The point: strings are USER-facing; bytes are WIRE-facing. Convert at
the boundary.

## Problem 4 (expert) — Concatenate and copy

`bytevector-append` joins two or more bytevectors:

```
(define header (bytevector 137 80 78 71))   ; PNG header bytes
(define body (bytevector 13 10 26 10))

(display (bytevector-append header body))
;; => #u8(137 80 78 71 13 10 26 10)
```

`bytevector-copy` makes a fresh copy — useful when the caller might
mutate the original.

```
(define original (bytevector 1 2 3))
(define twin (bytevector-copy original))

(bytevector-u8-set! twin 0 99)

(display original)
;; => #u8(1 2 3)
(display twin)
;; => #u8(99 2 3)
```

The mutation to `twin` didn't touch `original`. That is the copy
you paid for.

## Capstone — Build a tiny 'PNG-like' header

Not a real PNG (that would be a whole book), but the shape of
building a file header byte by byte.

```
(define (build-header magic width height)
  (bytevector-append
    magic
    (bytevector
      (quotient width 256) (modulo width 256)
      (quotient height 256) (modulo height 256))))

(define png-magic (bytevector 137 80 78 71 13 10 26 10))
(define header (build-header png-magic 640 480))

(display (bytevector-length header))
;; => 12
(display header)
;; => #u8(137 80 78 71 13 10 26 10 2 128 1 224)
```

Read the last four bytes: `2 128` encodes 640 as (2 * 256 + 128);
`1 224` encodes 480 as (1 * 256 + 224). That is big-endian 16-bit
integers written by hand.

You wouldn't normally write a real file format this way — you'd
reach for a proper encoder — but the SHAPE of manipulating bytes is
what this exercise teaches.

## Alphabet of bytevectors

- **Test:** `bytevector?`
- **Build:** `bytevector`, `make-bytevector`
- **Read:** `bytevector-u8-ref`, `bytevector-length`
- **Write:** `bytevector-u8-set!` (in-place)
- **Combine:** `bytevector-append`, `bytevector-copy`
- **Encode/decode text:** `string->utf8`, `utf8->string`

That's the whole family. Bytevectors don't compose with `map` and
`filter` directly — those are list verbs. If you want to transform
every byte, `bytevector-length` + `iota` + a manual loop is the
shape.

## What's next

In Chapter 7 we get string ports — the plumbing that lets Scheme
'read' from a string and 'write' to a string as if they were files.
That is how Motoi captures output and how you can programmatically
build strings without ever calling `string-append` in a hot loop.
")
